BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ace-pice-movilidad-2026-fase3@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260907
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260908
SUMMARY:Deadline: Accion Cultural Espanola: PICE Movilidad 2026 (Phase 3)
DESCRIPTION:PICE Movilidad is AC/E's collaboration scheme with foreign cult
 ural institutions: a festival\, biennial\, museum\, venue\, gallery or pla
 tform OUTSIDE Spain applies for AC/E to cover the costs of programming Spa
 nish or Spain-resident artists\, collectives and cultural professionals in
  its own public programme. This is one of the clearest routes for a non-Sp
 anish festival to have a foreign national fund pay for part of its program
 me. Ten thematic areas are covered including Artes visuales\, Musica y cre
 acion sonora\, Podcast\, Videojuego y animacion and Arquitectura y diseno\
 , so tech-crossover\, sound-art and media-art programming is squarely in s
 cope. For visual arts and architecture/design\, covered costs include prod
 uction materials\, purchase or rental of technical equipment\, hiring of t
 echnicians\, curators\, coordinators and designers\, reproduction and exhi
 bition rights\, logistics and transport of works\, publications\, document
 ation\, accommodation\, per diems\, travel and insurance\; for Musica y cr
 eacion sonora coverage is narrower (travel\, accommodation\, per diems\, i
 nternal transport). Non-EU and UK organisations are fully eligible\; there
  is no EU-membership requirement. Natural persons are barred. TIMING: Phas
 e 3 closes 7 September 2026\, provisional list 21 October\, definitive awa
 rd list 30 October\, and Phase 3 projects may not begin before 1 November 
 2026\, so this window cannot retro-fund an event already scheduled for aut
 umn 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Accion Cultural Espanola (AC/E)\nLocation: Anyw
 here outside Spain\, at the applicant's own venue or event. Applicant must
  be a foreign entity constituted outside Spain.\nAward: Max EUR 15\,000 pe
 r applicant per call\, per event and per thematic area\; within that\, max
  EUR 5\,000 per participant or collective. Total 2026 call budget EUR 1\,8
 10\,000 (Musica y creacion sonora EUR 320\,000\, Artes visuales EUR 200\,0
 00\, Videojuego y animacion EUR 90\,000\, Arquitectura y diseno EUR 90\,00
 0\, Podcast EUR 90\,000). Mandatory co-financing: the applicant must commi
 t at least 50 percent of each proposal's total budget. No application fee.
 \nDuration: Single event or project\; Phase 3 activities must start on or 
 after 1 November 2026 and finish before 28 February 2027.\n\nMore: https:/
 /www.accioncultural.es/es/movilidad-2026?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.accioncultural.es/es/movilidad-2026?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Anywhere outside Spain\, at the applicant's own venue or event. Ap
 plicant must be a foreign entity constituted outside Spain.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:terra-foundation-collections-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260803
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260804
SUMMARY:Deadline: Terra Foundation for American Art: Collections Grants (20
 26 cycle)
DESCRIPTION:Funds organisations to reinstall permanent collections or mount
  temporary exhibitions drawn primarily from their own holdings\, on condit
 ion the project broadens understandings of American art and pursues inclus
 ive\, expansive curatorial practice. Planning grants of USD 25\,000 to 75\
 ,000 cover research\, advisory committees and conservation\; implementatio
 n grants up to USD 100\,000 cover interpretation\, exhibition design\, con
 servation\, public programmes and dissemination of research\, so the publi
 c-programming layer of an exhibition is fundable here. TIMING: the 2026 cy
 cle is two-stage\, with a grant inquiry due 3 August 2026\, a full proposa
 l for shortlisted applicants due 13 October 2026\, external panel review\,
  decisions in April 2027 and projects starting after 1 May 2027. That is a
  nine-month decision lag\, so this is planning-horizon money. Internationa
 l applicants are explicitly welcomed and need US 501(c)(3) status or the i
 nternational equivalent. The Foundation will not fund acquisitions\, equip
 ment\, exclusively online projects\, or projects consisting primarily of l
 oans. The American-art subject requirement is the main constraint for medi
 a-arts organisations.\n\nOrganisation: Terra Foundation for American Art\n
 Location: Worldwide. Museums\, art centres and community-based cultural or
 ganisations both inside and outside the US.\nAward: Planning grants USD 25
 \,000 to 75\,000 (conservation capped at 25 percent of a planning award)\;
  implementation grants up to USD 100\,000. No formal match\, but the Found
 ation prefers not to be sole funder. No application fee.\nDuration: Projec
 t-based\; funded projects start after 1 May 2027 following April 2027 deci
 sions.\n\nMore: https://www.terraamericanart.org/what-we-offer/grant-progr
 am/collections-grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=re
 ferral
URL:https://www.terraamericanart.org/what-we-offer/grant-program/collection
 s-grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide. Museums\, art centres and community-based cultural orga
 nisations both inside and outside the US.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:terra-foundation-convening-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260928
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260929
SUMMARY:Deadline: Terra Foundation for American Art: Convening Grants (Roun
 d 1\, 2026-27)
DESCRIPTION:The most directly relevant Terra line for organisations running
  convenings rather than exhibitions: conversations\, symposia and workshop
 s that stimulate interdisciplinary and intercultural exchange. Covered cos
 ts are unusually broad and practical\, including professional fees\, artis
 t honoraria\, travel\, AV support\, interpretation and translation\, cater
 ing\, research dissemination\, marketing\, and administrative costs up to 
 20 percent. Awards run USD 10\,000 to 25\,000 and are made twice yearly. T
 he process is two-stage: Round 1 has a grant inquiry due 28 September 2026
  followed\, if invited\, by a full proposal due 30 November 2026\, for pro
 grammes taking place after 1 May 2027. Round 2 has an inquiry due 16 Febru
 ary 2027 and proposal due 20 April 2027 for programmes after 1 November 20
 27. Invited proposals go to an external panel of curators and arts profess
 ionals. International applicants are explicitly eligible and need US 501(c
 )(3) status or a recognised non-profit equivalent in their own country. Th
 e binding constraint is topical rather than geographic: a European or Asia
 n organisation can win this\, but the convening must engage American or In
 digenous North American visual art\, which is a workable frame for art-and
 -technology or sound-art programming with a US axis.\n\nOrganisation: Terr
 a Foundation for American Art\nLocation: Worldwide. Open to organisations 
 anywhere\, but subject matter must relate to the visual arts of the United
  States or Indigenous arts of North America.\nAward: USD 10\,000 to 25\,00
 0. Administrative costs capped at 20 percent of the grant. No formal match
  required\, but the Foundation prefers not to be sole funder. No applicati
 on fee.\nDuration: Event-based\; Round 1 supports programmes taking place 
 after 1 May 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.terraamericanart.org/what-we-offer/
 grant-program/convening-grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
URL:https://www.terraamericanart.org/what-we-offer/grant-program/convening-
 grants/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide. Open to organisations anywhere\, but subject matter mus
 t relate to the visual arts of the United States or Indigenous arts of Nor
 th America.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:japan-foundation-exhibitions-abroad-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261201
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261202
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Japan Foundation: Exhibitions Abroad Support Program 
 (FY2027-28 round)
DESCRIPTION:The Japan Foundation's flagship grant for organisations abroad 
 mounting an exhibition introducing Japanese art and culture\, explicitly c
 overing overseas biennials and triennials that present Japanese artists. I
 t is a partial-cost grant rather than a production budget: it pays toward 
 shipping Japanese works\, producing print or digital catalogues\, and brin
 ging Japanese artists\, curators and specialists to the venue. That cost s
 tructure suits media arts\, digital culture and art-and-science exhibition
 s well\, where shipping technical work and hosting the artist for installa
 tion are the main cost drivers. It is explicitly designed for non-Japanese
  applicants: museums\, galleries and comparable organisations outside Japa
 n. Institutions only\, so independent curators and artists cannot apply di
 rectly and must be hosted by an eligible institution. Exhibition content m
 ust introduce Japanese art and culture\, so a Japanese artistic component 
 is mandatory. Recent UK recipients include Tate Modern\, the V&A and the H
 ayward Gallery\, so the scheme skews toward established institutions. Appl
 icants are asked to discuss eligibility with the relevant regional arts pr
 ogramme officer before applying. FLAG: full FY2027 guidelines were not yet
  published by Tokyo headquarters as of July 2026 and this deadline is the 
 funder's own provisional date\; reconfirm in autumn 2026.\n\nOrganisation:
  The Japan Foundation\nLocation: Exhibition takes place at the applicant i
 nstitution's own venue outside Japan. National rounds run through Japan Fo
 undation offices worldwide.\nAward: No published ceiling. Partial-cost gra
 nt only: packing and shipping of Japanese exhibits (insurance excluded)\, 
 catalogue production including digital catalogues\, and travel for invited
  Japanese artists\, curators and specialists. Preliminary research and dev
 elopment explicitly excluded. The grant is partial by design\, so the host
  institution funds the balance. No application fee.\nDuration: Exhibitions
  must open between 1 April 2027 and 31 March 2028\; results notified April
  2027.\n\nMore: https://www.jpf.org.uk/artsandculture/funding.php?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.jpf.org.uk/artsandculture/funding.php?utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Exhibition takes place at the applicant institution's own venue ou
 tside Japan. National rounds run through Japan Foundation offices worldwid
 e.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:project-liberty-co-lab-fund-round-2-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260729
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260730
SUMMARY:Deadline: Project Liberty: Co-Lab Fund Micro-Grants (Round 2\, 2026
 )
DESCRIPTION:MEMBERS ONLY: this is a member-led collaboration fund\, not an 
 open public call. Projects must be led by a Project Liberty Coalition (All
 iance) member organization. Round 2 shifts to micro-grants of USD 10\,000 
 or less\, an iterative change from Round 1 intended to spread support acro
 ss more of the Coalition\; organizations that did not receive a Round 1 aw
 ard are preferred. SCOPE: micro-grants fund two kinds of work\, (1) discre
 te projects that strengthen the Coalition itself\, such as Shared Services
  or convenings\, and (2) time-sensitive collaborative projects within a de
 signated workstream. In both cases the work should begin quickly and produ
 ce something concrete. A STRONG APPLICATION SHOWS: work that builds the Co
 alition as an entity\, such as shared tools\, infrastructure or connection
 s that make joint action easier\; clear alignment with a Coalition workstr
 eam\; value for multiple Coalition organizations\; a strong case that the 
 work would not happen\, or would move more slowly\, without the Fund\; a c
 oncrete outcome such as a tool\, resource\, convening\, campaign or resear
 ch product\; and readiness to begin substantive work within two weeks of a
 pproval. LIMIT: one application per organization\, submitted through the e
 xisting Co-Lab Fund application form. Round 1 results were still pending a
 t the time of this call\, with funded projects to be shared soon and engag
 ement opportunities expected across the work. Prospective applicants unsur
 e whether an idea fits this round are invited to reach out first. DEADLINE
 : 29 July 2026 at midnight. Background on the Co-Lab program is in the Coa
 lition's overview document.\n\nOrganisation: Project Liberty (Alliance Ste
 erCo)\; pooled fund supported by Future of Life Institute\, Omidyar Networ
 k\, Ergo Impact\, and Project Liberty\nLocation: Members of the Project Li
 berty coalition (Alliance). Projects led by a Coalition member organizatio
 n\; geography otherwise unrestricted.\nAward: Micro-grants of USD 10\,000 
 or less\, a deliberate change from Round 1's larger awards so the Fund rea
 ches more of the Coalition. Preference given to organizations that did not
  receive a Round 1 award. No application fee.\nDuration: Short\, discrete 
 projects. Applicants must be ready to begin substantive work within two we
 eks of approval. This is the final round of the summer\; the Fund is expec
 ted to resume later in 2026.\n\nMore: https://forms.fillout.com/t/6AGEGhTk
 NJus?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://forms.fillout.com/t/6AGEGhTkNJus?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Members of the Project Liberty coalition (Alliance). Projects led 
 by a Coalition member organization\; geography otherwise unrestricted.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:antikythera-agentworld-journal-cfp-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260820
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260821
SUMMARY:Deadline: Antikythera Journal: Agentworld Special Issue\, Call for 
 Papers
DESCRIPTION:Antikythera\, a research programme on planetary computation and
  the evolution of intelligence\, invites contributions to Agentworld\, a s
 pecial issue of its peer-reviewed MIT Press journal launching Fall 2026. T
 HEME: Agentworld is a research initiative on the medium-term future of hyb
 rid human-AI societies\, framed not around tools for agentic task completi
 on but around what the brief calls 'the human perplexity of deep agentic d
 iffusion'. It treats human societies as the evolutionary niches into which
  new artificial species must adapt\, where the constraints of agentic inte
 gration are qualitative and open-ended (psychological\, philosophical\, li
 nguistic\, symbolic\, existential) rather than utility functions to be sol
 ved. The framing describes a 'parasociety' of densely reticulated social g
 raphs in which agent-to-agent communication constitutes most socially sign
 ificant interaction\, humans and agents anthropomorphise each other by inh
 eritance rather than necessity\, and the two overlapping societies act as 
 mutual evolutionary niches. The disciplinary posture proposed is 'a preemp
 tive anthropology of open-world centaur societies': building the vocabular
 y\, scenarios and conceptual armature for an emergent sociality while it i
 s still forming\, rather than describing it after the fact. WHAT THEY WANT
 : theoretical essays and technical papers that engage the Agentworld theme
 s directly and explain how the contribution adds to the special issue's co
 re questions. Philosophical\, theoretical\, technical\, design-led and pro
 duct-oriented research are all in scope. The call explicitly favours work 
 that exceeds conventional academic journal formats\, including contributio
 ns combining philosophical argument\, technical analysis\, design research
 \, diagrams\, software\, infrastructure proposals\, visual media or web-na
 tive formats. Contributors may optionally propose still images\, diagrams\
 , video\, web-based or interactive components\, and should say whether the
 y have the design\, development or production capacity to realise them\; t
 hese elements are not required. SUBMIT: an abstract or proposal of up to 5
 00 words\; author name(s)\, affiliation(s)\, contact details\, biography(i
 es) and CV(s)\; a designated lead author or contact person for collaborati
 ve submissions\; and a portfolio with at least one relevant work sample su
 ch as a preprint\, published article or paper. Full paper drafts are encou
 raged where available but not required at the initial stage. Submissions m
 ay be individual or collaborative. TIMING: the review window opened 25 Jun
 e 2026. NOTE: no closing date is published on the call page\; the deadline
  shown here is a placeholder set roughly a month out\, so check the site o
 r submit early.\n\nOrganisation: Antikythera (Antikythera: Journal for the
  Philosophy of Planetary Computation\, published with MIT Press)\nLocation
 : Remote (online submission\; the journal is web-first and design-forward)
 \nAward: Unpaid. No honorarium or fee is offered for accepted contribution
 s\; the return is peer-reviewed publication in the MIT Press-published Ant
 ikythera Journal. No submission fee.\nDuration: Single publication\; first
  selection of articles published Fall 2026\n\nMore: https://agentworld.ant
 ikythera.org/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral#ca
 ll-for-papers
URL:https://agentworld.antikythera.org/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantde
 sk&utm_medium=referral#call-for-papers
LOCATION:Remote (online submission\; the journal is web-first and design-fo
 rward)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-research-fellow-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260817
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260818
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI Research Fellow (AI Governance) 2026
DESCRIPTION:Research Fellows play a central role in GovAI's research: exper
 ienced researchers who conduct independent\, high-quality work with direct
  relevance to AI governance and policy while contributing to GovAI's intel
 lectual community. NOTE: applications open at the end of July 2026\; GovAI
  does not publish a fixed closing date\, so the 17 August 2026 date shown 
 here is just when this listing is set to expire (check the GovAI page for 
 the live status). Work may take the form of academic publications\, policy
  memos\, reports or blog posts\, alongside mentoring early-career research
 ers (such as Summer and Winter Fellows)\, shaping GovAI's research strateg
 y and convening stakeholders. Fellows work under a Senior Research Fellow 
 or leadership-team member but have substantial autonomy over projects\, ag
 endas and publication formats. TOPICS include risk management\, threat mod
 eling\, economics of AI\, geopolitics of AI\, public policy and technical 
 governance\; candidates working on adjacent topics are also welcome. ELIGI
 BILITY: open to a wide range of academic and professional backgrounds (com
 puter science\, political science\, public policy\, economics\, philosophy
 \, law\, plus government/industry/civil-society experience)\; no strict ed
 ucational requirement\, but the strongest candidates typically have multip
 le years of relevant research or policy experience and a track record of h
 igh-quality\, impactful work. A shared application also covers a one-year 
 visiting Research Scholar position for those with less experience (apply o
 nce for both). PROCESS: written application\; a paid remote work test (som
 e workstreams add a research agenda and a second paid test)\; then a final
  stage of two interviews and reference checks. Deep expertise in technical
  governance\, frontier safety design\, cybersecurity or US policy is espec
 ially welcome. Contact recruitment@governance.ai with location or access q
 uestions.\n\nOrganisation: Centre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocati
 on: London\, UK or Washington\, DC preferred\; open to candidates based el
 sewhere. UK visa sponsorship available\; US sponsorship only in exceptiona
 l cases.\nAward: Full-time 2-year fixed-term contract\, renewable. Salary 
 by experience and location: London typically GBP 85\,000-110\,000\; Washin
 gton DC typically USD 110\,000-180\,000\, with additional compensation for
  higher cost-of-living regions such as the SF Bay Area. Benefits: health\,
  dental and vision insurance\; GBP 5\,000 (~USD 6\,000) annual wellbeing b
 udget\; GBP 5\,000 (~USD 6\,000) annual professional-development budget\; 
 ~USD 500/month coworking for remote staff\; flexible hours\; extended pare
 ntal leave\; 10% employer pension contribution\; 33 days paid vacation (in
 cluding public holidays). No application fee.\nDuration: 2-year full-time 
 contract\, renewable\n\nMore: https://www.governance.ai/opportunities/rese
 arch-fellow?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/opportunities/research-fellow?utm_source=arti
 ficialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:London\, UK or Washington\, DC preferred\; open to candidates base
 d elsewhere. UK visa sponsorship available\; US sponsorship only in except
 ional cases.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:bloomberg-green-docs-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260814
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260815
SUMMARY:Deadline: Bloomberg Green Docs Competition 2026 (Short Climate Docu
 mentary)
DESCRIPTION:The Bloomberg Green Docs competition is open to all eligible fi
 lmmakers competing for a $25\,000 grand prize for a short climate document
 ary. The call seeks films that explore our climate future and reveal the w
 orld we are making today: ecosystems being restored\, tomorrow's zero-carb
 on communities being formed\, and habitat extremes warning of cascading cl
 imate consequences. REQUIREMENTS: films must address the urgency of climat
 e change and run under 10 minutes including credits. The jury awards a $25
 \,000 grand prize\, announced at the Bloomberg Green Docs Film Festival in
  New York City on 22 September 2026\, where the top five documentaries wil
 l be screened. Check the official rules on the competition site for eligib
 ility details. DEADLINE: submissions accepted through 14 August 2026.\n\nO
 rganisation: Bloomberg Green\nLocation: Open call for filmmakers (see elig
 ibility rules on the site)\; festival screening in New York City\, USA.\nA
 ward: $25\,000 grand prize awarded by a jury\; the top five documentaries 
 screen at the Bloomberg Green Docs Film Festival in New York City. No entr
 y fee stated.\nDuration: Winner announced at the festival on 22 September 
 2026\n\nMore: https://www.bloomberg.com/greendocs/?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.bloomberg.com/greendocs/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantd
 esk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Open call for filmmakers (see eligibility rules on the site)\; fes
 tival screening in New York City\, USA.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:new-emergence-art-prize-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260803
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260804
SUMMARY:Deadline: New Emergence Art Prize 2026
DESCRIPTION:The New Emergence Art Prize 2026 is an international open call 
 for emerging artists\, presented by New Emergence Art. There is no set the
 me and work may be submitted in any medium. AWARDS: a prize fund worth ove
 r GBP 5\,000 across nine awards supporting artists through cash prizes\, a
 rtist materials\, mentoring\, and a residency\, including a GBP 1\,000 Gra
 nd Prize\, a two-week NG Art Creative Residency in Provence\, France (wort
 h EUR 2\,000)\, a GBP 300 Founder's Prize cash award\, and materials or su
 bscription awards from Staedtler UK\, Rosemary & Co\, GreatArt\, Michael H
 arding\, and The Art Ladder. ELIGIBILITY: open internationally to emerging
  artists\; entrants may submit up to three original artworks that represen
 t the quality\, originality and direction of their practice. Final selecti
 ons are made by an independent judging panel considering concept\, executi
 on\, originality and impact. Shortlisted artists are featured in an online
  exhibition running 11 August to 7 September 2026. NOTE: there is a paid e
 ntry fee (amount set at the entry step). DEADLINE: 3 August 2026\, 23:59 B
 ST. Apply via https://www.newemergenceart.com/apply.\n\nOrganisation: New 
 Emergence Art\nLocation: International\; open worldwide. Shortlist shown i
 n an online exhibition.\nAward: Prize fund worth over GBP 5\,000 across ni
 ne awards\, including a GBP 1\,000 Grand Prize cash award\, a two-week NG 
 Art Creative Residency in Provence\, France (worth EUR 2\,000)\, a GBP 300
  Founder's Prize cash award\, and materials or subscription awards from St
 aedtler UK\, Rosemary & Co\, GreatArt\, Michael Harding\, and The Art Ladd
 er. NOTE: there is a paid entry fee.\nDuration: One-off prize\; shortliste
 d artists shown in an online exhibition 11 August to 7 September 2026\n\nM
 ore: https://www.newemergenceart.com/apply?utm_source=artificialnouveaugra
 ntdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.newemergenceart.com/apply?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrant
 desk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:International\; open worldwide. Shortlist shown in an online exhib
 ition.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:liu-shiming-artist-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: Liu Shiming Art Foundation: Artist Grants 2026
DESCRIPTION:The Liu Shiming Art Foundation's annual Artist Grants (fourth e
 dition) award up to five grants of USD 5\,000 each to early-career visual 
 artists to create new work exploring connections between traditional\, cul
 tural\, or historical influences and contemporary artistic practice. ELIGI
 BILITY: visual artists in the first decade of their career (two to ten yea
 rs practicing professionally)\; applicants must have received a studio-art
 s degree between 2016 and 2024\, or had their debut gallery or juried-exhi
 bition show between 2016 and 2026. Open to artists of any country\; the ap
 plication and all supporting materials must be in English. TIMELINE: appli
 cations open 1 June 2026\; close 31 August 2026\; recipients notified by 2
  December 2026. Apply via the Foundation's grants page.\n\nOrganisation: L
 iu Shiming Art Foundation\nLocation: Open to artists of any country\; appl
 ication must be in English.\nAward: Up to five grants of USD 5\,000 each. 
 Disbursed in two payments (USD 3\,000 by 15 January 2027 and USD 2\,000 on
  project completion). No application fee.\nDuration: Project grant for new
  work\n\nMore: https://www.lsmartfund.org/grants?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.lsmartfund.org/grants?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk
 &utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Open to artists of any country\; application must be in English.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:iias-asia-in-the-world-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260910
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260911
SUMMARY:Deadline: IIAS: Asia in the World Fellowship Programme 2027-2028
DESCRIPTION:The Asia in the World Fellowship Programme\, run by the Interna
 tional Institute for Asian Studies (IIAS) at Leiden University\, is a nine
 -month\, two-phase fellowship pairing a residency at a partner institution
  in Asia\, Africa\, Latin America\, or Europe (Phase 1) with six months in
  residence at IIAS in Leiden\, the Netherlands (Phase 2). The programme su
 pports interdisciplinary\, humanities- and social-science-based research e
 ngaging Asia and its connections with the wider world. SUPPORT during the 
 Leiden phase: EUR 1\,250 per month stipend\, EUR 1\,200 per month housing 
 allowance\, and a travel grant\; the Phase 1 stipend is provided by the co
 -host institution. ELIGIBILITY: scholars and researchers worldwide\; open 
 internationally. APPLICATIONS open 1 July 2026\; deadline 10 September 202
 6. Apply via the IIAS fellowships page. NOTE: dates confirmed via secondar
 y sources at time of entry (the funder page was not directly reachable)\; 
 verify before applying.\n\nOrganisation: International Institute for Asian
  Studies (IIAS)\, Leiden University\nLocation: Two phases: a partner insti
 tution in Asia\, Africa\, Latin America\, or Europe (Phase 1)\, then Leide
 n\, Netherlands (Phase 2). Open internationally.\nAward: Leiden phase: EUR
  1\,250 per month stipend plus EUR 1\,200 per month housing allowance\, pl
 us a travel grant\; the Phase 1 stipend at the co-host institution is set 
 by that institution. No application fee.\nDuration: 9 months (two phases)\
 n\nMore: https://www.iias.asia/fellowships/asia-in-the-world?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.iias.asia/fellowships/asia-in-the-world?utm_source=artifici
