SUMMARY:Deadline: Lee Ufan Arles: Prix Art & Environnement 2026 (Residency 
 + Exhibition Prize)
DESCRIPTION:The Prix Art & Environnement (4th edition)\, awarded by Lee Ufa
 n Arles and Maison Guerlain\, supports an artist working at the intersecti
 on of art and the natural environment. The prize winner receives a funded 
 6–8 week production residency in Arles in early 2027\, including product
 ion space\, accommodation\, and mentorship from Lee Ufan Arles staff\, cul
 minating in a solo summer 2027 exhibition. ELIGIBILITY: open to all artist
 s of any discipline and nationality\, with no age or degree requirements\;
  candidates must demonstrate at least one solo exhibition and one or more 
 group exhibitions. DEADLINE: 31 July 2026. APPLY via the Google Form linke
 d from the Lee Ufan Arles website.\n\nOrganisation: Lee Ufan Arles and Mai
 son Guerlain\nLocation: Arles\, France (residency and exhibition)\nAward: 
 Funded residency (production space + accommodation) in Arles. No cash priz
 e amount specified. No application fee.\nDuration: 6–8 weeks residency i
 n early 2027\, followed by a solo summer 2027 exhibition\n\nMore: https://
 en.leeufan-arles.org/evenements/art-environment-prize?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://en.leeufan-arles.org/evenements/art-environment-prize?utm_sourc
 e=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Arles\, France (residency and exhibition)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:longview-digital-minds-grants-applied-work-2026@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260711
SUMMARY:Deadline: Longview Philanthropy: Digital Minds Grants for Applied W
 ork 2026
DESCRIPTION:Longview Philanthropy invites proposals for applied work on the
  potential consciousness\, sentience\, moral status\, or experiences of AI
  systems. Typical grants are $50\,000–$2\,000\,000 per project\, with pr
 oposals outside that range considered when justified. New organisations ma
 y also receive some operational support. ELIGIBLE ACTIVITIES: seed funding
  for new organisations (think tanks\, research bodies\, initiatives)\; men
 torship programmes for researchers entering the digital minds field\; inte
 rnships\, new hires\, or focused programmes on digital minds at existing A
 I organisations\, academic labs\, or policy institutions\; convenings and 
 field-building (workshops\, conferences\, summits\, working groups address
 ing technical and governance questions). AREAS OF INTEREST: measuring AI w
 elfare\; consciousness and sentience research\; governance and legal/socia
 l science frameworks for potentially sentient AI\; communications work for
  thoughtful public discourse\; research beyond the US\; support organisati
 ons and operations professionals for independent technical researchers. SE
 LECTION CRITERIA: potential impact\, track record\, demonstrated interest 
 in digital minds and its relationship to AI risk\, cost-effectiveness\, le
 gal compliance. Deadline: 10 July 2026. Questions: digitalminds-rfp@longvi
 ew.org. Apply at https://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-a
 nd-applied-work-on-digital-minds/.\n\nOrganisation: Longview Philanthropy\
 nLocation: Worldwide / remote (grant-eligible countries listed in applicat
 ion form)\nAward: Typical grants $50\,000–$2\,000\,000 per project\; pro
 posals outside this range considered when the work justifies it. May inclu
 de some operational support for new organisations. No application fee.\nDu
 ration: Project-based\; duration varies by scope.\n\nMore: https://www.lon
 gview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-work-on-digital-minds
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-wor
 k-on-digital-minds/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
LOCATION:Worldwide / remote (grant-eligible countries listed in application
  form)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:longview-digital-minds-research-fellowships-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260710
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260711
SUMMARY:Deadline: Longview Philanthropy: Digital Minds Research Fellowships
  2026
DESCRIPTION:Longview Philanthropy Research Fellowships support scholars pur
 suing research on the potential consciousness\, sentience\, moral status\,
  and legal position of AI systems. AMOUNT: $55\,000–$120\,000/year (thro
 ugh a university\, with 10% research budget and standard fringe benefits)\
 , or $80\,000–$150\,000/year (direct stipend\, with suggested 5–10% al
 location for research and travel). Compute resources available for machine
  learning research. Invitation and funding to attend the annual Center for
  Mind\, Ethics\, and Policy Summit at NYU. ELIGIBILITY: must have or be ex
 pected to receive a doctoral degree in computer science\, neuroscience\, a
  related technical discipline\, law\, medicine\, or applied social science
  by September 2027 or fellowship start date (exceptions for equivalent res
 earch experience)\; fellows arrange their own institutional affiliation\; 
 fellowship may be conditional on institutional affiliation or attendance a
 t events. SELECTION CRITERIA: demonstrated interest in digital minds and i
 ts relation to AI risk\; evidence of research promise (publications\, acad
 emic achievements\, references). DURATION: 1–2 years\; second year condi
 tional on ongoing programme requirements. AREAS OF INTEREST: introspection
 \, welfare measurement\, interpretability\, model character\, correlates o
 f consciousness\, valence research\, governance frameworks\, legal and pol
 itical responses to potentially sentient AI. Deadline: 10 July 2026. Requi
 red application materials: CV\, description of possible research direction
 s (~1\,000 words)\, intended outcomes\, what you would do without this fel
 lowship (~150–400 words)\, career goals (~300 words). Questions: digital
 minds-rfp@longview.org. Apply at https://www.longview.org/request-for-prop
 osals-research-and-applied-work-on-digital-minds/.\n\nOrganisation: Longvi
 ew Philanthropy\nLocation: Worldwide / remote or institutional (grant-elig
 ible countries listed in application form)\nAward: $55\,000–$120\,000/ye
 ar through a university\, or $80\,000–$150\,000/year direct stipend\; pl
 us research budget (10% of salary)\, conference travel\, and compute resou
 rces where applicable. No application fee.\nDuration: 1–2 years. Second 
 year conditional on continuing to meet programme requirements.\n\nMore: ht
 tps://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-work-on-
 digital-minds/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.longview.org/request-for-proposals-research-and-applied-wor
 k-on-digital-minds/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
LOCATION:Worldwide / remote or institutional (grant-eligible countries list
 ed in application form)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:revitalizing-rituals-2026-open-call@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260719
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260720
SUMMARY:Deadline: Revitalizing Rituals 2026 Open Call
DESCRIPTION:Revitalizing Rituals invites artists from all disciplines -- so
 und\, movement\, visual arts\, installation\, performance\, and transdisci
 plinary practices -- to join a research-creation journey across two landsc
 apes: Bhar Lazreg in Tunisia and the wetlands of Somogy County in Hungary.
  The project explores rituals as living forms of belonging: reconnecting c
 ommunities\, land\, memory\, food\, ecological reciprocity\, and the more-
 than-human world. Selected artists work with local communities as co-parti
 cipants in a shared inquiry into moving from extraction toward reciprocity
 . Organised by Homo Faber Alapítvány (Hungary). AMOUNT: EUR 6\,000 gross
  artist fee and production budget\; international travel and per diems cov
 ered\; on-site accommodation provided. ELIGIBILITY: minimum 5 years of act
 ive artistic practice\; portfolio reflecting interest in situated or relat
 ional work\; no formal degree required\; working language is English (loca
 l language navigation valued)\; must be available for the full residency c
 ycle including all international travel\; must be able to legally receive 
 the fee and invoice the organising partners from country of residence. Str
 ongly encourages applications from historically marginalised or underrepre
 sented voices. KEY DATES: Application Deadline 19 July 2026 (midnight) -- 
 note the open call PDF also references a 5 July date\; the officially prom
 oted deadline is 19 July\; Online Q&A 29 June 2026\, 14:00 Tunisia / 15:00
  CET (register at https://forms.gle/brnZvXvFe4JB8zL26)\; Online Conversati
 ons with shortlisted artists: mid July to mid August 2026\; Selection Resu
 lts: 31 August 2026\; Placemaking Camp: 1 week\, end of November 2026\, Hu
 ngary\; Storytellers Camp: 1 week\, March 2027\, Tunisia\; Residency Perio
 d: minimum 1 month (splittable)\, April to July 2027\; Final Presentation:
  August 2027\; Closing Event: 3 days\, winter/early spring 2028\, Hungary.
  Apply via the open call form linked at https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/up
 loads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf.\n\nOrganisation: 
 Homo Faber Alapítvány (Homo Faber Foundation)\nLocation: Bhar Lazreg\, T
 unisia and Somogy County\, Hungary\; multi-stage in-person residency acros
 s both sites.\nAward: EUR 6\,000 gross artist fee and production budget\; 
 international travel and per diems covered\; on-site accommodation provide
 d. No application fee.\nDuration: Multi-stage residency: Placemaking Camp 
 (1 week\, November 2026\, Hungary)\; Storytellers Camp (1 week\, March 202
 7\, Tunisia)\; Residency Period (minimum 1 month\, April-July 2027)\; publ
 ic presentation (August 2027)\; Closing Event (3 days\, winter/early sprin
 g 2028\, Hungary).\n\nMore: https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/uploads/2026/0
 6/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-in-the-RR-form.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://homofaber.hu/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Artist-Open-Call-FINAL-
 in-the-RR-form.pdf?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referr
 al
LOCATION:Bhar Lazreg\, Tunisia and Somogy County\, Hungary\; multi-stage in
 -person residency across both sites.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:she-got-game-emerging-talents-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: Game Design Emerging Talents: She Got Game
DESCRIPTION:She Got Game is a Pro Helvetia mentoring programme promoting eq
 ual opportunities in the Swiss and international game industry\, supportin
 g the representation of women in management positions through dialogue wit
 h experienced international experts from the game industry. The call is ai
 med at professional game designers who identify as women from the regions 
 of Pro Helvetia's liaison offices: the Arab region\, East Asia\, South Ame
 rica\, South Asia and Vietnam\, and West\, Central\, East and Southern Afr
 ica. ELIGIBILITY: Emerging Talents are game developers or game studios who
 se relevant training or registration (self-employed\, sole proprietorship\
 , or company) dates back less than seven years. Selection criteria include
  digital content for devices such as computers\, consoles\, mobile devices
 \, or mixed-reality devices requiring a high level of interaction\; clearl
 y defined objectives in terms of participation and career\; originality\, 
 feasibility\, degree of innovation\, and marketability of the project\; an
 d project leaders holding the copyright and rights of use. Excluded: commi
 ssioned work and projects that are part of an advertising or promotional c
 ampaign\, and purely technological projects without obvious narrative and/
 or aesthetic content. WHAT IS OFFERED: individual coaching and input talks
  on project development\, business strategy and finances\, marketing\, PR\
 , and pitch training\; involvement in a growing community of female game d
 evelopers\; potential access to international trade fairs\; CHF 3\,000 tow
 ard the production of a prototype or demo version\; and up to CHF 250 per 
 week toward childcare or children's travel expenses when attending interna
 tional trade fairs (a budget must be presented in advance). All modules ar
 e conducted in English\; the programme is a time-consuming commitment of r
 oughly 30 hours over six months\, plus potential additional time attending
  events or trade fairs. APPLICATION: submit a short CV (including educatio
 n/training\, nationality\, and residency status in Switzerland)\, a short 
 description of the current project (type and genre\, gameplay\, platform\,
  development status\, target audience\, with relevant visual material\, ma
 x. 10 A4 pages)\, a project portfolio\, and expectations regarding the pro
 gramme's objectives. All documents should be submitted in English\; if not
  possible\, applications may be submitted in German\, French\, or Italian.
  KEY DATES: applications open 1 July 2026\; submission deadline 1 Septembe
 r 2026\, 23:59 CEST\; notification of decision in November 2026\; earliest
  project start 1 January 2027. Apply via the Pro Helvetia application port
 al.\n\nOrganisation: Pro Helvetia (Swiss Arts Council)\nLocation: Remote/i
 nternational mentoring programme\; applicants must be based in one of Pro 
 Helvetia's liaison-office regions (Arab region\, East Asia\, South America
 \, South Asia and Vietnam\, and West\, Central\, East and Southern Africa)
 .\nAward: CHF 3\,000 toward the production of a prototype or demo version\
 , plus individual coaching and community access\; potential access to inte
 rnational trade fairs. When attending trade fairs\, applicants with childc
 are responsibilities can request up to CHF 250 per week for childcare or c
 hildren's travel expenses. No application fee.\nDuration: Six-month mentor
 ing programme\, approximately 30 hours total commitment\; notification in 
 November 2026\; earliest project start 1 January 2027.\n\nMore: https://pr
 ohelvetia.ch/en/find-support/game-design-emerging-talents-she-got-game-3/?
 utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://prohelvetia.ch/en/find-support/game-design-emerging-talents-she
 -got-game-3/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote/international mentoring programme\; applicants must be base
 d in one of Pro Helvetia's liaison-office regions (Arab region\, East Asia
 \, South America\, South Asia and Vietnam\, and West\, Central\, East and 
 Southern Africa).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:prohelvetia-international-promotion-institutions-outside-switzerland-20
 26@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260901
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260902
SUMMARY:Deadline: International Promotion: Institutions Outside Switzerland
  (Literature)
DESCRIPTION:Pro Helvetia's international promotion grant (institutions outs
 ide Switzerland variant) supports organizations abroad promoting contempor
 ary Swiss literary works and authors at book fairs\, festivals\, and event
 s (analogue\, digital\, or hybrid). Open to event organizers\, publishing 
 houses\, professional associations\, or digital platforms based outside Sw
 itzerland\; no Swiss residency or nationality is required\, but projects m
 ust feature Swiss books\, authors\, or translators together with Swiss par
 tner organizations. AMOUNT: maximum CHF 25\,000. Deadlines twice a year: 1
  March (23:59 CET) and 1 September (23:59 CEST). Apply via the Pro Helveti
 a portal.\n\nOrganisation: Pro Helvetia (Swiss Arts Council)\nLocation: Ev
 ent organizers\, publishing houses\, professional associations\, and digit
 al platforms based outside Switzerland\; projects must feature Swiss books
 /authors/translators and Swiss partners.\nAward: Maximum CHF 25\,000. No a
 pplication fee.\nDuration: Promotion project featuring Swiss literature\; 
 deadlines twice yearly (1 March and 1 September).\n\nMore: https://prohelv
 etia.ch/en/find-support/international-promotion?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://prohelvetia.ch/en/find-support/international-promotion?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Event organizers\, publishing houses\, professional associations\,
  and digital platforms based outside Switzerland\; projects must feature S
 wiss books/authors/translators and Swiss partners.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:small-file-media-festival-2026-call-for-work@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260701
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: Small File Media Festival 2026 - Call for Work
DESCRIPTION:The Small File Media Festival 2026 invites moving-image submiss
 ions under the theme "Can Small Files Save the World?" -- a call for artho
 use\, video work\, glitch aesthetics\, punk\, sci-fi\, narrative\, and doc
 umentary work made with a small-file mindset. This year the festival espec
 ially welcomes small-scale experiments with narrative and documentary. The
  festival frames Small File Ecomedia as a political and ecological interve
 ntion: small files function in regions with precarious infrastructure\, ci
 rcumvent bandwidth imperialism and surveillance\, and expose the environme
 ntal cost of mainstream online video. WHAT THEY WANT: craftily composed\, 
 elegantly performed\, and artfully minimised movies in any genre\; use of 
 obsolete technologies\, creative compression techniques\, and low-bandwidt
 h aesthetics at all stages of production is encouraged. Resources for maki
 ng small-file work at www.smallfile.ca/make. Open to artists\, activists\,
  media pirates\, rogue technologists\, and filmmakers. No payment or submi
 ssion fee stated. All submitted information used for festival programming 
 and promotion -- ensure accurate spelling\, punctuation\, and capitalisati
 on. Submissions close 1 July 2026 at midnight. Submit at https://smallfile
 .ca/submit/.\n\nOrganisation: Small File Media Society\nLocation: Canada\;
  festival screening. Open to international submissions.\nAward: No payment
  stated\; festival programming and screening. No submission fee stated.\nD
 uration: One-time festival screening.\n\nMore: https://smallfile.ca/submit
 /?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://smallfile.ca/submit/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
LOCATION:Canada\; festival screening. Open to international submissions.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:adk-ems-berlin-stockholm-residency-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: AdK / EMS Berlin-Stockholm Bilateral Residency Program 20
 26-27
DESCRIPTION:A new bilateral residency collaboration between the Studio für
  Elektroakustische Musik at the Akademie der Künste in Berlin and Elektro
 nmusikstudion EMS in Stockholm. Four artists will be selected to develop a
 nd present new works in both cities\, with presentations at KONTAKTE 2027 
 in Berlin and at a corresponding event in Stockholm. The program supports 
 new artistic and technical initiatives at the intersection of sound\, musi
 c\, and technology in the field of time-based\, performative\, and digital
  arts. ELIGIBLE CATEGORIES: (1) new instrumental and live-electronic works
 \; (2) acousmatic music\, computer music\, radio art\, and other forms of 
 electroacoustic music and sound art\; (3) projects from artists of any dis
 cipline for whom sound is a central element\; (4) curatorial\, publishing\
 , and educational projects in sound-based art practice\, particularly thos
 e relating in content to the AdK Studio or EMS\; (5) independent research 
 in acoustics\, computer science\, or musicology -- specifically software d
 evelopment\, spatialization\, or network technologies. Open to individuals
  and groups. Project duration is flexible and arranged by agreement. SUPPO
 RT: travel and accommodation costs for Berlin and Stockholm covered\; pres
 entation fees paid for both venues. Selection is made by the director and 
 advisory board of the Studio für Elektroakustische Musik and the director
  of EMS\; decision is final with no legal entitlement to funding. Incomple
 te or late applications are not considered. This call supplements the Stud
 io's regular residency program (separate deadline June 30\, 2026 for July-
 December 2026 period). Apply exclusively via the online form at https://nc
 .adk.de/index.php/apps/forms/s/HD2nxbzqwgeMHWN6xHg9bQrA. Questions: estudi
 o@adk.de. Deadline: 31 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Studio für Elektroakus
 tische Musik\, Akademie der Künste (Berlin) and Elektronmusikstudion EMS 
 (Stockholm)\nLocation: Berlin\, Germany and Stockholm\, Sweden\; travel an
 d accommodation covered for stays in both cities.\nAward: Travel and accom
 modation costs for stays in Berlin and Stockholm covered\; fees paid for p
 resentation at KONTAKTE Festival 2027 (Berlin) and for presentation in Sto
 ckholm. Amount not publicly stated. No application fee.\nDuration: Flexibl
 e\, by agreement\; works to be presented at KONTAKTE 2027 in Berlin and at
  a Stockholm presentation.\n\nMore: https://nc.adk.de/index.php/apps/forms
 /s/HD2nxbzqwgeMHWN6xHg9bQrA?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://nc.adk.de/index.php/apps/forms/s/HD2nxbzqwgeMHWN6xHg9bQrA?utm_s
 ource=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Berlin\, Germany and Stockholm\, Sweden\; travel and accommodation
  covered for stays in both cities.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:democracy-stories-lab-open-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260722T105922Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260914
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260915
SUMMARY:Deadline: Democracy Stories Lab: Open Call for Visual Storytellers
DESCRIPTION:The Democracy Stories Lab\, an initiative of People Powered (a 
 global hub for participatory democracy) in partnership with the Democracy 
 Narratives Alliance\, invites creators worldwide to submit visual content 
 -- short videos\, illustrations\, or graphics -- that tells a compelling s
 tory about democracy\, voice\, fairness\, belonging\, and community power.
  Content can be original or already published\, as long as it is the appli
 cant's own work and engages with narrative frameworks from the Democracy N
 arratives Alliance's research on 'How to Talk About Democracy.' Tone is op
 en\; serious and comedic approaches are both welcome. SUBMISSIONS: up to t
 wo finished visual content pieces per applicant\, answering the prompt of 
 what the future would look like if people had a real say in the decisions 
 that shape their lives. FORMATS: primarily visual social media content\, i
 ncluding short videos (under 3 minutes\, vertically oriented) and illustra
 tions\; written or audio pieces are accepted if presented in a visual form
 at\, for example as a filmed performance. Each submission should build on 
 one of five narrative types from the DNA research brief 'How to Talk About
  Democracy': outcome-oriented (how democracy shows results)\, intrinsic-va
 lue (why democracy is the best choice)\, collectivist (the importance of d
 iverse voices)\, individual (how democracy is empowering) and process-orie
 nted (showing democratic institutions work)\; a short creative brief gives
  further guidance. AWARDS: 4 winning entries receive USD $1\,000 each\; 5 
 honorable mentions receive USD $500 each\; all winners receive amplificati
 on across People Powered and Democracy Narratives Alliance communications 
 networks and are featured in a global screening event. WHO CAN APPLY: indi
 vidual creators and small teams anywhere in the world\; especially welcome
 s creators who reach audiences outside usual democracy circles\, who come 
 from communities traditionally with less of a say in public discourse\, an
 d who work in civic tech\, advocacy\, community organising\, comedy\, art\
 , illustration\, games\, or lifestyle content. Applications opened 14 July
  2026 and are submitted through the official form on the People Powered De
 mocracy Narratives Alliance page. Submission deadline: 14 September 2026. 
 Winners announced October-November 2026. Note: the initiative was itself v
 oted into existence through People Powered's participatory budgeting proce
 ss (PP Decides).\n\nOrganisation: People Powered and Democracy Narratives 
 Alliance\nLocation: Worldwide\; remote. Global screening event for winners
 .\nAward: USD $1\,000 for each of 4 winners\; USD $500 for each of 5 honor
 able mentions. Plus amplification across People Powered and Democracy Narr
 atives Alliance networks and feature in a global screening event. No appli
 cation fee.\nDuration: One-time award.\n\nMore: https://www.peoplepowered.
 org/news-content/announcing-the-democracy-stories-lab?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.peoplepowered.org/news-content/announcing-the-democracy-sto
 ries-lab?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Worldwide\; remote. Global screening event for winners.
END:VEVENT
